          "body": "Two parallel love-commands anchor the chapter, both with the formula *love X as yourself*. Verse 18 commands love of *rea* (neighbor), the fellow Israelite. Verse 34 commands love of *ger* (resident alien), the non-Israelite. The two commands together rule out the reading of v.18 as ethnocentric — the Torah itself extends the love-formula across ethnic lines. Jesus' parable of the Good Samaritan (Luke 10:25-37) is not a novel ethic but a faithful exposition of Lev 19:18 + 19:34. Paul declares v.18 the summary of the entire law (Rom 13:9; Gal 5:14). Verse 17 sharpens what love requires: not silence, but honest reproof — *you may surely reprove your neighbor, but shall not incur sin because of him*. Love is willing to risk the relationship by telling the truth; hatred is willing to harbor a grudge while keeping the peace."
